5. STEP-BY-STEP IMPLEMENTATION ORDER
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

─── PHASE 0: Interfaces ────────────────────────────

Step 1: Create interfaces

  Create 3 files in `functions/src/interfaces/`:
    blogPost.ts  → BlogPost interface (title, text, imgUrl, category, authorId, authorName, publishedOn, views, votes)
    category.ts  → Category interface (label)
    report.ts    → Report interface (mostViewedPostId, mostUpvotedPostId, mostDownvotedPostId, topCategory, topCategoryVotes, worstCategoryVotes, date)

─── PHASE 1: Core CRUD (HTTP endpoints) ────────────

Step 2: Update constants.ts — add REPORT_TIME

  Find src/Helpers/constants.ts and add at the end of the export object:
    REPORT_TIME: process.env.REPORT_TIME || "08:00",

Step 2: Create DataAccess/Write/setBlogPost.ts

  Purpose: A helper function that writes a new blog post to the database.

  What it does:
    - Takes title, text, category, imgUrl, authorId, authorName
    - Creates an object with those fields + publishedOn (current time), views: 0, votes: 0
    - Calls defaultDB.ref("posts").push(postObject) to save it
    - Returns the new post's unique ID

  Look at the existing DataAccess/Write/setSomething.ts for the pattern.

Step 3: Create DataAccess/Read/getBlogPosts.ts

  Purpose: Return blog posts with optional filters and pagination.

  What it does:
    - Reads all posts from defaultDB.ref("posts")
    - Applies filters if query params exist (by title, text, category, author, view count)
    - Sorts by publishedOn (newest first)
    - Slices results for pagination (page + limit params)
    - Returns the filtered/sorted/sliced array

  Tip: reading from RTDB returns an object, not an array.
  Use snapshot.forEach() or Object.keys().map() to convert to an array.

Step 4: Create DataAccess/Read/getBlogPost.ts

  Purpose: Return a single blog post by its ID.

  What it does:
    - Reads defaultDB.ref("posts/{postId}").once("value")
    - Returns the post data (or null if not found)

Step 5: Create CloudFunctions/cfCreatePost.ts

  Purpose: HTTP endpoint — POST /blogPosts. Creates a new blog post.

  What it does:
    1. Check Authorization header for Bearer token
    2. Verify token with admin.auth().verifyIdToken(token)
       (this gives you the user's uid)
    3. If invalid/missing, return 401
    4. Extract title, text, category, imgUrl from request body
    5. Validate required fields (title + text are mandatory)
    6. Call setBlogPost() with the data + author info
    7. Return the new post as JSON

Step 6: Create CloudFunctions/cfGetPosts.ts

  Purpose: HTTP endpoint — GET /blogPosts. Returns paginated, filtered posts.

  What it does:
    1. Extract query params from URL: title, text, category, author, view, viewOp (gt/lt/eq), page, limit
    2. Call getBlogPosts() with those filters
    3. Return the array as JSON

  To test filters:
    GET /blogPosts?category=tech&page=1&limit=10
    GET /blogPosts?title=hello
    GET /blogPosts?view=gt&val=5

Step 7: Create CloudFunctions/cfGetPost.ts

  Purpose: Auth-guarded endpoint — GET /blogPosts/<id>. Returns a single post
           and records a "first view" if the user hasn't read it before.

  What it does:
    1. Verify auth token (like cfCreatePost)
    2. Get postId from the URL
    3. Call getBlogPost(postId)
    4. If not found, return 404
    5. Write to readReceipts/{postId}/{uid} with value true
       (this triggers cfRtdbOnFirstView which increments the view count)
    6. Return the post as JSON

Step 8: Create CloudFunctions/cfUpdatePost.ts

  Purpose: Auth-guarded endpoint — PUT /blogPost/<id>. Updates a post.

  What it does:
    1. Verify auth token
    2. Get postId from URL
    3. Get existing post — verify the authorId matches the authenticated uid
       (users can only edit their own posts)
    4. Extract updated fields from request body
    5. Call defaultDB.ref("posts/{postId}").update(updatedFields)
    6. Return success

Step 9: Create CloudFunctions/cfDeletePost.ts

  Purpose: Auth-guarded endpoint — DELETE /blogPost/<id>. Deletes a post.

  What it does:
    1. Verify auth token
    2. Get postId from URL
    3. Verify ownership (authorId === uid)
    4. Call defaultDB.ref("posts/{postId}").remove()
    5. Also clean up: remove any votes for this post
    6. Return success

Step 10: Wire everything in index.ts

  Open src/index.ts and add:
    import { cfCreatePost } from "./CloudFunctions/cfCreatePost";
    import { cfGetPosts } from "./CloudFunctions/cfGetPosts";
    import { cfGetPost } from "./CloudFunctions/cfGetPost";
    import { cfUpdatePost } from "./CloudFunctions/cfUpdatePost";
    import { cfDeletePost } from "./CloudFunctions/cfDeletePost";

    export const createPost = cfCreatePost;
    export const getPosts = cfGetPosts;
    export const getPost = cfGetPost;
    export const updatePost = cfUpdatePost;
    export const deletePost = cfDeletePost;

─── PHASE 2: Votes (Callable functions + DB triggers) ────

Step 11: Create DataAccess/Read/getVote.ts

  Purpose: Check if a user has already voted on a post.

  What it does:
    - Reads defaultDB.ref("votes/{postId}/{uid}").once("value")
    - Returns the value (1 = upvote, -1 = downvote, null = no vote)

Step 12: Create DataAccess/Write/setVote.ts

  Purpose: Set or remove a vote.

  What it does:
    - Takes postId, uid, vote value (1, -1, or 0 to remove)
    - If vote is 1 or -1: defaultDB.ref("votes/{postId}/{uid}").set(vote)
    - If vote is 0: defaultDB.ref("votes/{postId}/{uid}").remove()

Step 13: Create CloudFunctions/cfUpvote.ts

  Purpose: Callable function — upvote a post (only once).

  What it does:
    1. context.auth is automatically populated (no manual token check needed)
    2. Get postId from data parameter
    3. Call getVote(postId, uid) to check existing vote
    4. If already upvoted (vote === 1), return error "already upvoted"
    5. If already downvoted (vote === -1), change to upvote (setVote with 1)
    6. If no existing vote, set vote to 1
    7. Return success

Step 14: Create CloudFunctions/cfDownvote.ts

  Same as cfUpvote but checks for "already downvoted" and sets vote to -1.

Step 15: Create CloudFunctions/cfRevokeVote.ts

  Purpose: Remove a vote if the user already voted.

  What it does:
    1. Get postId from data
    2. Call getVote(postId, uid)
    3. If no existing vote, return error "no vote to revoke"
    4. Call setVote(postId, uid, 0) to remove
    5. Return success

Step 16: Create CloudFunctions/cfRtdbOnVote.ts

  Purpose: Database trigger — updates the post's total score when a vote changes.

  What it does:
    1. Trigger: functions.database.ref("/votes/{postId}/{uid}").onWrite
    2. Get the new vote value and old vote value from the event
    3. Calculate the difference: newVote - (oldVote || 0)
       Example: old = -1, new = 1 → diff = 2 (score goes up by 2)
    4. Update the post's votes field:
       defaultDB.ref("posts/{postId}/votes").transaction(v => (v || 0) + diff)
    5. This way, the post always shows the correct total score

Step 17: Update index.ts

  Add:
    import { cfUpvote } from "./CloudFunctions/cfUpvote";
    import { cfDownvote } from "./CloudFunctions/cfDownvote";
    import { cfRevokeVote } from "./CloudFunctions/cfRevokeVote";
    import { cfRtdbOnVote } from "./CloudFunctions/cfRtdbOnVote";

    export const upvote = cfUpvote;
    export const downvote = cfDownvote;
    export const revokeVote = cfRevokeVote;
    export const rtdbOnVote = cfRtdbOnVote;

─── PHASE 3: Auth trigger ─────────────────────────

Step 18: Create CloudFunctions/cfAuthOnSignup.ts

  Purpose: When a new user creates an account, automatically create
           a profile for them in the database.

  What it does:
    1. Trigger: functions.auth.user().onCreate
    2. Gets user object (has uid, email, displayName, etc.)
    3. Writes to defaultDB.ref("profiles/{uid}").set({
         email: user.email,
         displayName: user.displayName || "Anonymous",
         createdAt: Date.now()
       })
    4. That's it — no return needed

Step 19: Update index.ts

  Add:
    import { cfAuthOnSignup } from "./CloudFunctions/cfAuthOnSignup";
    export const authOnSignup = cfAuthOnSignup;

─── PHASE 4: Database triggers ────────────────────

Step 20: Create DataAccess/Write/setView.ts

  Purpose: Mark that a user has read a post (used by cfGetPost).

  What it does:
    - Takes postId and uid
    - Writes true to defaultDB.ref("readReceipts/{postId}/{uid}")
    - This is a no-op if the receipt already exists (the write is the same)

Step 21: Create CloudFunctions/cfRtdbOnFirstView.ts

  Purpose: Database trigger — when a read receipt is created for the first time,
           increment the post's view count.

  What it does:
    1. Trigger: functions.database.ref("/readReceipts/{postId}/{uid}").onCreate
       (only fires when the node is CREATED, not on subsequent writes)
    2. Get postId from context.params
    3. Increment: defaultDB.ref("posts/{postId}/views")
         .transaction(v => (v || 0) + 1)
    4. This means each user only counts as one view, ever

Step 22: Create CloudFunctions/cfRtdbOnNewPost.ts

  Purpose: Database trigger — when a new post is created, ensure
           views and votes are initialized to 0.

  What it does:
    1. Trigger: functions.database.ref("/posts/{postId}").onCreate
    2. Get the post data from the snapshot
    3. If views or votes are missing, set them to 0:
       defaultDB.ref("posts/{postId}").update({ views: 0, votes: 0 })

Step 23: Update index.ts

  Add:
    import { cfRtdbOnFirstView } from "./CloudFunctions/cfRtdbOnFirstView";
    import { cfRtdbOnNewPost } from "./CloudFunctions/cfRtdbOnNewPost";
    export const rtdbOnFirstView = cfRtdbOnFirstView;
    export const rtdbOnNewPost = cfRtdbOnNewPost;

─── PHASE 5: Storage trigger (image resize) ───────

Step 24: Create CloudFunctions/cfStorageOnImageUpload.ts

  Purpose: When an image is uploaded to Storage, resize it to a square
           and rename it to {authorName}_post_{timestamp}.

  What it does:
    1. Trigger: functions.storage.object().onFinalize
       (runs when a file finishes uploading)
    2. Get file info: object.name (file path), object.contentType
    3. If not an image, skip (return early)
    4. Download the file to a temp location (/tmp/)
    5. Use sharp to resize to a square (e.g. 500x500, crop to center)
    6. Upload the resized image back to Storage with the new name
    7. Delete the temp file
    8. Update the post's imgUrl to point to the new resized image

  Note: In the emulator, Storage runs locally.
        The file will be in the emulator's local storage directory.

Step 25: Update index.ts

  Add:
    import { cfStorageOnImageUpload } from "./CloudFunctions/cfStorageOnImageUpload";
    export const storageOnImageUpload = cfStorageOnImageUpload;

─── PHASE 6: Reports (PubSub + HTTP) ──────────────

Step 26: Create DataAccess/Read/getReports.ts

  Purpose: Return reports, optionally filtered by date.

  What it does:
    - Reads defaultDB.ref("reports")
    - If date param is provided, filter reports by that date
    - Returns the matching reports

Step 27: Create DataAccess/Write/setReport.ts

  Purpose: Save a daily report to the database.

  What it does:
    - Takes reportData (most viewed post, most upvoted, etc.)
    - Pushes to defaultDB.ref("reports").push(reportData)

Step 28: Create CloudFunctions/cfPubsubDailyReport.ts

  Purpose: Runs every day at REPORT_TIME. Analyzes all posts and
           generates a report with stats.

  What it does:
    1. Schedule: functions.pubsub.schedule("0 ${REPORT_TIME} * * *").onRun
       (This runs every day at the hour and minute specified by REPORT_TIME)
    2. Read all posts from defaultDB.ref("posts")
    3. Calculate:
       - Post with most views
       - Post with most upvotes (highest votes)
       - Post with most downvotes (lowest votes)
       - Category with the most posts
       - Category with highest total votes
       - Category with lowest total votes
    4. Save the report using setReport()
    5. console.log the results

Step 29: Create CloudFunctions/cfGetReports.ts

  Purpose: Auth-guarded HTTP endpoint — GET /reports.

  What it does:
    1. Verify auth token
    2. Get optional date query param
    3. Call getReports(date)
    4. Return reports as JSON

Step 30: Update index.ts (final)

  Add:
    import { cfPubsubDailyReport } from "./CloudFunctions/cfPubsubDailyReport";
    import { cfGetReports } from "./CloudFunctions/cfGetReports";
    export const pubsubDailyReport = cfPubsubDailyReport;
    export const getReports = cfGetReports;

